  "source_notes": "Sy Scholfield quotes from ''Hand-books of Natural Philosophy and Astronomy, Volume 3'' by Dionysius Lardner (Blanchard and Lea, 1854), page 313, \"on Sept. 1, 1804, at ten o'clock, p.m., Professor Harding, of Lilienthal, discovered another minute planet.\" Same data in other books such as ''The solar system, a descriptive treatise'' by John Russell Hind (1851).\\nOn 7 March 2025 Lianne McCafferty sent a scan of p. 246 from the book ''Lilienthalische Beobachtungen der neu entdeckten Planeten Ceres, Pallas und Juno'' by JH.Schröter [https://dn790006.ca.archive.org/0/items/lilienthalische00schrgoog/lilienthalische00schrgoog.pdf] which reports the original observations by Harding. The time of first observation is given as 10:12 pm. This source was already previously recorded since 2015 in [https://www.astro.com/astrowiki/de/Juno Astrowiki].\\n",
